{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582466"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.15,0.03,0.05,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92390"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/191"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5851"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92390"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a nine month history of recurrent, sudden episodes where he feels that the room is spinning around him. Each episode is accompanied by nausea and ringing in his left ear. He has also noticed that it has been increasingly difficult to hear lower-pitched sounds in the same ear. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. Weber\u0027s test reveals lateralisation to the right ear and the Rinne test shows air conduction is greater than bone conduction in both ears.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebellopontine angle tumour","Vestibular neuronitis","Presbycusis","Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","M\u00e9ni\u00e8re\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EM\u00e9ni\u00e8re\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E commonly occurs in middle-aged individuals. It is characterised by recurrent attacks of vertigo, associated with progressive sensorineural hearing loss, nausea, vomiting, tinnitus and aural fullness. It may sometimes present with horizontal nystagmus. Sensorineural hearing loss is established on the tuning fork tests, where lateralisation to the right ear indicates impaired sensorineural hearing function of the left ear. A normal Rinne test indicates normal conductive hearing bilaterally. Lower frequencies tend to be affected initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in younger patients. Although it may also present with vertigo, it is not associated with progressive hearing loss. Symptoms usually only last 6-12 weeks and patients often complain of ear pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with hearing loss. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebellopontine angle tumours\u003C/strong\u003E (such as acoustic neuroma) can present similarly to M\u00e9ni\u00e8re disease - unilateral sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, vertigo. However, these patients may present with unsteady gait and symptoms of other cranial nerve disturbances, such as facial numbness or weakness. Nevertheless, in this case it would be essential to rule out a diagnosis of malignancy by performing a gadolinium-enhanced MRI of the brain and internal acoustic meatus and this should be undertaken in patients with new onset sensorineural hearing loss. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Epresbycusis\u003C/strong\u003E (age-related hearing loss) is sensorineural in nature, it is not associated with recurrent vertigo attacks. It also differs to M\u00e9ni\u00e8re disease in that it initially affects the higher frequencies, rather than lower frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["M\u00e9ni\u00e8re\u0027s disease is characterised by recurrent attacks of vertigo, associated with progressive sensorineural hearing loss, nausea, vomiting, tinnitus and aural fullness"],"references":["Gibson WPR. Meniere\u0027s disease. Adv Otorhinolaryngol.\u00a02019;82:77-86. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30947172/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T15:52:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T15:52:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"191"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92390"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro